segments.text: Okay, let's talk about the fire.
Oh, yeah.
As far as you, when was the, when did the building burn?
It was 1979, I think it was February 28th.
It was right at the end of February.
And it began during the night.

yeah apparently began early in the morning and some students i believe spotted it and called in the alarm may have been some students from hotard hall which is the next building over and i think they called in the alarm and the fire department came and and jack williams
and Margaret were living in that apartment at the time.

That of course was after Frank had retired, and he and Rosemary had gone to South Carolina, and so the students helped the Williamses get a lot of their stuff out, and the building was pretty much destroyed.
When did you
first here?
Oh, it was while I was getting ready for work.
I had just gotten up and I was in the shower and Chris came to the door and said, Margaret is on the phone and... Margaret Ingram.
Margaret Ingram.
And she says the press burned down.
Of course, I immediately ended my shower and got out and got in the car and drove up here.
And...
What did it look like?
Well, it was still smoking, of course, when I got here, and the hoses were still across the yard, and there was stuff all over the yard that the firemen had thrown out of the building.
It was a real mess.
You could tell the whole top floor practically was gone.
The roof, of course, was all gone.
And so we sort of stood in the yard with our jaws open and wondering what we were going to do.
Was there anything, were you able to even get up to where your office was?
Not at that time.
Of course, the firemen wouldn't let us up for several hours until they got everything cooled down and they soaked things really good.
Were the flames gone when you all got there?
Was the building no longer flaming?
Yeah, it was still smoking, but the flames were out.
So we stood around there and waited until the fire department declared it was safe.
I think we were able to poke around in some of the stuff they had thrown through the windows from the second floor.
So we recovered some books and papers and manuscripts and stuff that they had thrown out of the second floor windows

clear the way so that they could fight the fire and we found some stuff that we needed but then after we were able to go in we went up and started going through the rooms and and trying to salvage whatever we could and we carried carry it up and down those soaking stairs with the smell of charred wood and
We did that for several days, just carrying stuff down.
And we'd take it down to the warehouse, mainly files and manuscript pieces and things like that.
We'd carry them down to the storage room, which was the old garage I mentioned earlier.
And we'd lay wet paper out in the sun and weight it down with rocks to let it dry so that we could figure out what it was and what to do with it.
We still have some papers in our old files, some old historical files that still have the water stains and little bits of insulation stuck to them.
Did you lose any personal sentimental priceless items?
No, I didn't.
I didn't have anything that was
Easily damaged.
And my office, being in the back, wasn't burned.
There wasn't really any flame back there.
It was mostly water damage and wet plaster from the ceiling stuck to things.
So the fire was worst in the west side, the front of the building?
Right.
Right.
In the conference room area.
And particularly on the southwest corner where Ray Grimala's office was, they figured that it probably started in the attic above his office.
And the building was being remodeled, the inside was being remodeled, and it may have begun from work that was being done there, but nobody really knows for sure.
Did you see, when you got there, were either of the Williamses around?
No, I don't recall.
I mean, we were all in shock.
And I don't think so.
By the time I got there, I think they were both gone.
But I don't remember seeing them.
But those first few days are pretty much a blur in my memory.
in hindsight, could anybody identify some manuscripts that were totally destroyed?
Yeah, we lost some things.
I think the worst loss was some artwork for one of Bill Brett's books, one of his short story books.
They were by a friend of his in East Texas, and they'd been laid out to
for us to look at to see how they would fit with the story.
Of course, they were irreplaceable, and they were all destroyed.
And the original of Tom Lee's drawing of the logo, wasn't it damaged?
The final one, it was not, because it was framed separately.
But it was all the preliminary drawings he had done for the press logo, and they were all framed together in a large frame,
And that was on the wall that apparently the water just streamed down that wall and into the frame and soaked everything, ran the ink and ruined it.
But the other single drawing and letter was in a separate frame on a separate wall.
We had a lot of papers and proof spread out on the table in Frank's office, which had been originally the board meeting room.
And so we had a lot of stuff on that big table.
And when the ceiling collapsed, this huge light fixture that was almost as long as the table and just as wide
came right straight down on top of all those papers and protected everything on that table from the fire.
So we pushed that light fixture off the table.
There was everything that we had left, just perfect.
Hadn't even been touched by the flames or the water.
It had been protected by that huge piece of ceiling.
Were there any
particular artworks you remember that were destroyed?
No, just the, just the, no, this was, it was Lloyd's office then, of course, and Lloyd had less artwork on his walls than Frank had had, because
He only had a few photographs.
Frank had a whole wall of photographs behind his desk of friends and authors.
And if those had been there, those would have been destroyed.
But Lloyd had not put up as much artwork.
He did have one of those pewter centennial plates that the university had made in 76.
And we still have that in the vault, and about half of it is melted away with the pewter just kind of dripping off the edge.
Oh, really?
And that was on the wall behind the desk.
So if anything, paper had been on that wall, it would have been charred or burned up.
But no, the rest of the press, we lost a lot of reference books and business documents, orders that we were processing at that time, which were out on the desks, were damaged or destroyed.
But I don't remember any other than those drawings by Bill Brett's friend.
I don't remember of anything.
valuable artistically speaking.
We had a vault at the time.
It was in that garage shipping room warehouse, and a lot of the artwork was in that vault.

Now, you all moved things for a few days, the staff, the press staff did, and did the university offer to have people come over to help move, or did you all assume this yourself, feeling it would be better if you all did it?
Well, people volunteered.
Jerry Cooper was one of the people who volunteered and came over and spent long hours helping us carry stuff out.
But it was mainly just the staff.
About how long was it before you all began to do press work again?
Well, of course, there were some things we had to keep going immediately.
And we worked out of the warehouse.
We set up phones and desks.
salvaged the furniture that we could and put it in the warehouse.
We moved books away from the west wall of the warehouse and used uh set the desks up along there and that's those were our offices.
Describe that setup and about what size was that?
Oh it was probably
Well, it was wide enough to get two cars in, so it's at least 20 feet across.
I think maybe it's even wider than that, probably like 30.
It's probably about 30 by 40, something like that.
Was it floored?
Concrete.
Concrete?
Just bare concrete.
And the walls were?
Well, they were concrete block with wooden book bins built all along both sides.
And the air conditioning and heating system?
We opened the garage doors in the summer on warm days, I should say, because spring was coming along.
It started getting warmer.
But we had some cold days after that, too, and I remember sitting there in my heavy coat with a little electric heater blowing on my feet, and that was the heat.
And the lighting?
Well, we had lamps plugged into the desks, but it was basically just warehouse-style lighting hanging from the ceiling.
And were there cords across the floor at the very end?
Yeah.
And was it divided into workspaces?
There weren't any interior walls, were there?
No, no.
We just had our desks more or less organized by department.
About how many people were working, how many individuals were working in there?
A dozen?
Well, yeah.

all of the I think we're up to about 12 people at the time and of course they were trying to ship ship and and package books at the same time over on the other side now the the material that had been in the warehouse to begin with was not damaged that's right so the the books for shipment they were not
Right.
Just the stuff that was in the main building.
Describe how Lloyd, as the director, how he handled this crisis.
Well, he got everything organized pretty quickly and got the university to get us set up in that warehouse space.
We were using the university's
I'm not sure if we were using the university's computer system or if we were still working with the University of Texas Press, but at any rate, the computer services didn't break down.
We just kept operating like we normally would.
Now, in my interview with Mrs. Williams, she kind of felt that the university didn't do all that it could have done
to help them move things and find things and so forth.
Did you all feel that the press had been left out in that emergency?
I think most of us were so wrapped up in keeping the books going and recovering what we could that
I didn't really pay that much attention to what the university was doing.
My feeling was that the university didn't react quickly enough in finding us an alternate space, because it was a couple or three months before we got the temporary trailers in.
And then they moved those up
once after they brought the trailers in, then they moved them up to another location, and then it was three years until we got the new building.
Now, where?
Four years, actually.
Yeah, four years.
Those trailers were put where?
Well, they started out on the corner towards
right across from where the University Mail Center is now, and was then.
And then a few weeks later, they were moved up closer to University Drive on the corner next to Hotard Hall.
And I'm not sure what the street is off University, but it's across from the old Methodist Church there on University.
And you had how much of a trailer as your workspace?
I had one desk and a room and a trailer.
We had three big trailers and a small one.
The big ones were, I think they were 60-foot trailers.
So these were like an 18-wheeler pulls, that kind of trailer?
Yeah, like a mobile home.
Oh, like a mobile home, okay.
Like a trailer you see at a work site.
Okay.
And these, and so they had heating and cooling.
Right.
Electric blowers.
All right.
And you shared a trailer with whom?
Well, Lloyd's office was at one end, and Margaret's office was at the other end.
And Mary Lynn, who was with us then, and I worked in the center section.
We had two desks set in there.
Right.
Now, you mentioned Mary Lynn Dixon.
She joined the press when compared to you?
She started in, let's see, 78.
September 78, I think.
And you started?
In 75.
In 75.
So she came three years after you.
She'd only been with the press a few months when the fire happened.
Oh, oh.
All right, and Margaret Ingram stays till early?
Early 81.
Okay.
And then I became the managing editor then.
just editor it was called.
Describe what that promotion meant.

Well that meant that I was doing more acquisitions and Lloyd was doing some but then I really started doing acquisitions and started working heavily and recruiting authors and getting manuscripts for the press and at the same time though I was still managing the
copy editing and scheduling copy editors and scheduling projects going into production.
When did you first begin to have copy editors report to you?
Well, Mary Lynn did.
When she came?
No, in 81 when I became the editing editor.
She was reporting to Margaret before that.
But not until then.
Did you have others reporting to you?
Right, right.
Okay.
All right.
Then in 81, when that began, what kind of advising or prepping did you give to a new editor, new copy editor?
Well, we didn't have any new copy editors until Susan Nessler came on in 84 or 85.
What, wasn't Mary Lynn a new one?
No, she was, she'd already, she started in 78.
Oh, in 78.
Oh, oh, oh, oh, okay, oh, okay.
But we had, we had an editing test that we gave candidates.
Really?
Yeah, and that's sort of frowned on by human resources now, but, but no, we required
copy editor, prospective editor to come in and take a test and see how proficient they were.
Can you describe any of the key questions?
No, there were just samples of manuscript and lists of sentences that may or may not have needed correction of one kind or another.
It was just to get an idea of how aware the person was of
of English punctuation, grammar, and spelling, and also good judgment in how to deal with different styles and what to allow and what to question.
Now, normally an editor has a what kind of degree background?
Yours was journalism.
Well, it varies much.
You really can't say.
I think most copy editors probably have a journalism or English background.
But nowadays, there are so many different kinds of editors.
They do so many different jobs.
Acquisitions editors are often specialists in the field they acquire in.
So there's as many different specialties as there are people, I think.
Let's go back to, I forgot that Frank left before the fire.
When did you all learn that he was going to retire, and how did you learn?
Well, he hired Lloyd to come in as assistant director in, it must have been, it was in the summer of 77.
So it was then that he announced that he was going to be retiring in another year.
All right.
So he did announce it.
Yeah.
And that Lloyd would come in and work with us for a year and then be the director, become the director, frankly.
Now, Lloyd Lyman is L-Y-M-A-N. That's right.
And he came from where?
He was at LSU Press.
But he had only been there for a year or two before he was hired to come here.
And he was their number two man?
Right.
I think he was assistant director or perhaps editor in chief when he was there.
Describe the last months of Wardlaw.
Did Frank work at the same speed and effort as always?
Oh, yeah.
And in fact, even after he left and they moved to South Carolina,
He took work with him and worked on a kind of a freelance basis after that, especially with art books.
He put together two of the art series books after he had left College Station.
If we could talk to him now and ask him what his favorite A&M Press book would have been, what do you think his favorite might have been?
I don't know.
I'd have to think about that.
Would it be art, you think?
I think so.
I think so.
Maybe.
He always wanted Buck Shewitz to do another art book for us.
Buck had done that series of prints of A&M campus, and Frank loved Buck's
He always wanted Buck to do a book for us, but really the book never was, never got out until after Frank had left.
Why not?
Well, it was getting Buck Shewitz to do the work.
And getting him to sit down and tell his story so that someone could transcribe it and write it up.
And never did do that, I think.
And was Buck living at the old board house while you were there?
Right.
He was directly downstairs from me at that time.
All right, please share with this machine all the Buck Shewitz memories you have.
Oh, Buck was such a character.
First of all, describe him physically.
What did Buck look like?
Well, he was a stocky, white-haired fellow with a thick,
German-Texan accent.
He could hardly understand him sometimes.
He had such a thick accent.
I think he put a lot of it on, and a lot of people speculated on that.
But it fit him perfectly, his personality.
He liked to mix up his English words and get them all confused.
And his office was directly below mine, and so I saw him a lot.
And he'd be down there drawing and say hello to him as I came and went, and visit with him a little bit.
But he wasn't always there.
He did quite a bit of traveling, even while he was supposedly in residence in College Station.
And I remember one time when a
particular TV series was coming on.
I told Buck that my wife and I wanted to see that with our daughter, because it was a family kind of TV show that was coming on.
And Buck had this huge, I guess for those days, it was huge.
Must have been a 27-inch TV set in his suite.
And he said, will you all come down and use it?
I'm going to be gone.
You can use my suite and watch that show.
And so we did.
We went into Buck's suite and watched the show on TV one night.
And he had a workspace there, and he had a table.
He didn't keep a lot of his artwork out unless he was actually working on it.
And if he didn't like what he was doing, if he was disappointed or unhappy with something, he would tear it up and throw it away.
And so occasionally you'd see in the trash can, you'd see these crumpled, destroyed pieces of paper with this wonderful stuff on it.
And I often wished that I had...
had the guts to ask him for some of that before he crumpled it up and threw it away.

Sometimes, though, he would deface something before he threw it away by, like if he was doing a beautiful building, architectural rendering of one of the central Texas German homes or something, and he messed up on it, in his opinion, and made a mistake, well, then he would...
I would do a cartoon of a jet airliner flying over it, something like that.
I'm shaking my head because the same thing I'm saying to myself, why, why, why, nothing else?
Didn't I go over there and go through the trash?
Now, as far as you knew, while he was there in residence, for whom was he doing those works of art?
Were they to sell to anyone?
Yes, right.
And I think he sold fairly regularly.
I don't know how hard he tried.
I know he had patrons, people who almost collected his art.
I think the Lindsay's did that.
And I know there's other people around the state who have good collections of Buck Shewitz's work.
Now, his wife was deceased by then.

i think right well no she she was she was not deceased she was hospitalized oh okay and he was living there in that right in the in the suite where he downstairs from where he did the art right uh where did he eat his meals do you know i think he ate at sabisa and he ate with frank and roseberry on too did he have a car during that time did he even drive
I think he did have a car.
Yeah, I think he was still driving.
Now, on occasion, I know that Buck drank too much.
Did Joel ever have any experience of his?
I never did.
You didn't see him pass down anything?
No.
He wasn't there more than a year, a year and a half.
after I got here.
And then he went back to, I believe, Wimberley.
And he had a little place there where he lived and worked.
Was he a congenial neighbor?
Oh, yeah.
For you all?
Yeah, sure.
He was great.
He was just a wonderful man.
And our daughter was only four or five years old then, and everybody
You know, she attracted people, and Buck was one of the people who thought she was just a little doll, and so he would always say something to her, and Frank and
and Rosemary treated her like one of their grandkids.
Let's see, we haven't described Rosemary.
We haven't talked about her much.
Well, Rosemary is just the perfect other half for Frank, I think.
She loved to read, but she wasn't a person who was interested in making books herself or doing any writing herself.
But she...
kept the home for Frank and was perfect hostess for the kinds of things that Frank enjoyed, getting people together and talking and enjoying their company.
Now, when they lived downstairs below the press, did she come upstairs much?
Not very much.
Didn't see her upstairs very much.
And did Frank normally go downstairs to eat lunch?
Oh, yes.

he'd go downstairs for lunch and maybe to um to take a little nap after lunch and then he'd be back up around two o'clock probably did he ever bring any desserts or anything from downstairs up to serve the group i don't think so i don't recall that once in a while um
